img.title: see also: https://iaap-journals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/apps.12247;

https://iaap-journals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/apps.12249
Retraction: Roy Thurik, Anis Khedhaouria, Olivier Torrès, Ingrid Verheul, “ADHD symptoms and entrepreneurial orientation of small firm owners”, Applied Psychology: An International Review, 2016, 65(3), 568-586: https://doi.org/10.1111/apps.12062. The above article from Applied Psychology: An International Review published online on 16th February 2016 in Wiley Online Library (wileyonlinelibrary.com) has been retracted. The paper has been retracted by full agreement between the authors, the Journal’s Editors, Ute Stephan, Nele De Cuyper and Tomoki Sekiguchi, and John Wiley & Sons. The retraction was initiated by the authors when they discovered that they were unable to recompute the reported link between ADHD and Entrepreneurial Orientation (EO) in Table 2 of their article. The authors have revisited the raw data and created a corrected data file for replication purposes. They did so in the context of a larger study exploring the link between ADHD and EO which led to richer and more robust results. This larger study has been accepted for publication by Applied Psychology: An International Review as a research note. Its bibliographical details are: Annelot Wismans, Roy Thurik, Ingrid Verheul, Olivier Torrès and Katsuyuki Kamei (2020), “Attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder symptoms and entrepreneurial orientation: a replication note.” Applied Psychology: An International Review, (https://doi.org/10.1111/apps.12247).

https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/03056244.2019.1668650
We, the Editors and Publisher of Review of African Political Economy, have retracted the following article:
Oluwaniyi, Oluwatoyin O. 2018. “The Role of Multinational Oil Corporations (MNOCs) in Nigeria: More Exploitation Equals Less Development of Oil-rich Niger Delta Region.” Review of African Political Economy 45 (158): 558–573. doi:10.1080/03056244.2018.1546687.
The above-named Review of African Political Economy article has been retracted and should not be cited. Following publication of the above article in print and online, it has been determined that the paper has been previously published elsewhere.
The Editors together with the publishers of the journal, Taylor & Francis, note that we received, peer-reviewed, accepted, and published the article on the basis of warranties made by the author regarding its originality and provenance.
We have been informed in our decision-making by our publishing ethics and the Committee on Publication Ethics (COPE) guidelines on retractions.
The retracted article will remain online to maintain the scholarly record, but it will be digitally watermarked on each page as “Retracted”.

img.title: EOC Text: 'The substance of the concern is that the fit statistics reported in the article may contain many errors. The journal has investigated the matter with the help of a committee of methodology experts in statistical technique. The committee has come to the conclusion that there may indeed be something wrong with the statistics provided in the article. However, it is difficult to ascertain the implications of these errors unless the raw data is made available. Unfortunately, the authors were not able to provide the raw data despite repeated requests. We feel it is important for our readership to be aware of potential issues with the results reported in this article. We would like to reiterate that authors should be able to provide raw data when requested by journals and editors. Providing access to data when requested is good scientific practice, and is encouraged by this journal.'

img.title:
Digital All Stars is a new series of articles on Ventureburn and Memeburn, which recognises and celebrates achievement in a variety of digital fields that includes entrepreneurship, media & marketing, technology innovation, general business and education. Our aim with the Digital All Stars Series on Ventureburn is to celebrate entrepreneurial achievement in South Africa, and the African countries in which Ventureburn is popular in, which includes Kenya and Nigeria.
Creating lists to recognise achievement is, in itself, a fraught exercise, so we aim to ensure accuracy by consulting with many experts in the wider industry to ensure that we acknowledge all who are achievers and leaders in their fields. In the article “13 South African tech entrepreneurs on the rise” it has come to our attention that we did not apply this process rigorously enough, and the article is not reflective or inclusive enough.
Quite simply, the article and the research that went into it is not in sync with the high standards we set ourselves in our mission to build the entrepreneurial landscape in South Africa, Kenya and Nigeria.
We apologise unreservedly for this error in judgement. We will try harder. We will fix this. And we will be back with an article that celebrates the digital and entrepreneurial stars on our continent.

img.title: JE Hunton responsible for unreliable data;

Robert Libby and Kristina Rennekamp, “Self-serving attribution bias, overconfidence, and the issuance of management forecasts,” Journal of Accounting Research, vol. 50, no. 1 (March 2012). Section 4 of the above-referenced paper includes empirical analysis based on survey data obtained from Dr. James E. Hunton. Because of concerns raised by the Bentley Report (available at https://www.bentley.edu/files/Hunton%20report%20July21.pdf) about the inability to independently verify data that form the basis for certain of Dr. Hunton's published works, the editors of JAR and the authors of the above-referenced article hereby issue an Expression of Concern with respect to this article. Specifically, the authors have concluded that the validity of the survey data that underlie Section 4 of this article cannot be confirmed, and suggest that the inferences readers draw from the article be adjusted accordingly.

Original article published on https://www.ahpanet.com

Retraction Press Release: 'Honey Holding I, Ltd dba Honey Solutions, an industrial honey processor, announced today that it has obtained a second retraction in less than one year from the American Honey Producers Association ('AHPA'). The AHPA posted an admittedly untrue and incorrect representation on its AHPA website stating that Honey Holding was criminally charged with involvement in actions related to the illegal transshipment of Chinese honey.
On or about March 7, 2015, the Pittsburgh Tribune published an article stating that Honey Holding had knowingly sold tainted honey from China containing corn syrup or sugar and that the government had charged Honey Holding with tax evasion. Just two days later, on March 9, 2015, the AHPA republished on its website the Tribune article containing those libelous and defamatory statements. Honey Solutions requested that the Tribune and AHPA remove the incorrect statements. Consequently, the Pittsburgh Tribune voluntarily removed the erroneous and incorrect statements from their March 7th online article.'

img.title: see also http://www.ava.com.au/13296

T he September 2014 issue of the Australian Veterinary Journal and the website of the Australian Veterinary Association (AVA) included an article regarding the product Tri-Solfen. The article contained inaccuracies for which the AVA; its President, Dr Julia Nicholls; and its Media & Campaigns Manager, Ms Rena Richmond, would like to apologise and retract. The AVA is now in receipt of a scientific report from Professor Peter Windsor that concludes that the risk of residues in food producing animals is extremely low, and a scientific report from Professor Jock McLean that concludes that the risk of residues harmful to humans is non-existent following use of Tri-Solfen. Further, Professor McLean concludes “the risk is known and is essentially zero”. The AVA acknowledges that it is unaware of any published data contradictory to the comments of Professor Windsor and Professor McLean set out above and that, based on those comments, the conclusions in the article regarding residues were erroneous. Tri-Solfen is a critical and important animal welfare advance that has been widely used to reduce suffering and improve wound healing in Australian sheep. The AVA acknowledges that it has the potential to provide important animal welfare advances in other species. The AVA, Dr Nicholls and Ms Richmond sincerely apologise to Bayer Australia Limited, Animal Ethics Pty Limited and Provet Pty Limited for the inaccuracies contained within the article. For more information about Tri-Solfen and its current registration, please contact Bayer Animal Health on 1800 678 368 https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/avj.135

Abstract: Notice of Retraction
After careful and considered review of the content of this paper by a duly constituted expert committee, this paper has been found to be in violation of IEEE's Publication Principles.
We hereby retract the content of this paper. Reasonable effort should be made to remove all past references to this paper.
The presenting author of this paper has the option to appeal this decision by contacting TPII@ieee.org.
In this article, we utilize the research methods of complex network to discuss the inter-province knowledge spillover in China based on paper cooperation from 1980 to 2009. We analyze the topology of the knowledge spillover network by measuring the degree distribution, average path length, clustering coefficient, clustering and degree correlation, and find that the (1)degree distribution is similar to power-law distribution in 1980–2000, and then tend to anti power-law distribution; (2)Both Lag and Catch-up of regions did appeared in different times; (3)Average path length and clustering coefficient have large fluctuate, and(4) there is obvious clustering and degree correlation. By analyzing the relationships between topology characteristics combining with realistic background, we reach the conclusion that (1)the weak ties are more, (2)public policy to improve inter-district knowledge cooperation has been carried out efficiently and(3) key points are more vital. At last we predict the developing trend of inter-province knowledge spillover.
